Key Commands
The following are some of the most commonly used Git commands: 
Command 	Description
git init	Initializes a new local Git repository in the current directory.
git clone [url]	Creates a local copy of a remote repository from a specified URL.
git add [file]	Stages changes for the next commit. Can be a specific file or all modified files.
git commit -m "[message]"	Records the staged changes as a new commit with a descriptive message.
git status	Shows the status of files as untracked, modified, or staged.
git branch [name]	Lists, creates, or deletes branches.
git checkout [branch-name]	Switches to a different branch (in newer Git versions, git switch is an alternative).
git merge [branch]	Combines the history and changes from one branch into the current branch.
git pull	Fetches changes from the remote repository and merges them into the local branch.
git push	Uploads local branch commits to the remote repository.
